kmeans() Function

The kmeans() function is useful in predicting different variable types. The easiest way for me to explain this function is to describe every input.

It is important to note that when this function is called, because it is a prediction function, prediction needs to be random. This means you need to set a seed using set.seed().

The function is called in this style:

kmeans(x, centers, iter.max = 10, nstart = 1, algorithm = c("Hartigan-Wong", "Lloyd", "Forgy", MacQueen"), trace = FALSE))

x

This is simply the data frame that you use to predict clusters.

centers

This just means the number of clusters or groups that you want the function to predict. So if youre predicting pitch types, how many pitches do you want the function to predict?

iter.max

This is how many times that the function runs through the data to try and predict clusters. Basically the default setting of the function is it double checks itself 10 times.

nstart

The clusters need to be random, so this tells the function how many random sets are chosen.

algorithm

Honestly, I know this will change the results, somehow, or the method that the function uses to get the results which could cause different results than another algorithm, but I dont know if this matters.

What Does kmeans() Return?

It returns a lot of stuff honestly. Lets go through each individually.

centers

A matrix of how many of each predicted type was found for each cluster.

totts

Total sum of squares. So basically the total error.

withinss

Basically this is a vector of all errors within each individual cluster.

tot.withinss

Basically each of the entries of withinss summed up. This is different than the totts though so dont get the two confused.

betweenss

This is the difference between totts and tot.withinss, so

\[betweenss = totts- tot.withinss\]

size

How many of each cluster are found.

iter

The number of times the clustering was repeated.

Example

I was given the Trackman data for three former pitchers at Vanderbilt University. I was asked to play with the kmeans() function to find interesting predictors for pitch type. So, lets dive in.

I decided to use predictors other than RelSpeed, Tilt, and SpinRate because those are the variables that we use when actually tagging. I honestly thought that would be boring to look at. Outside of those however, there are few variables to use in predicting solely based on the metrics of the pitch. For the purpose of this assignment, I am only looking at predictors that are not dependent on the result of the play.

Should I have time, I will be interested in looking at result of the play to determine PitchType because that can identify a pitchers weak pitches. This would allow an understanding of what pitches they are more likely to throw for a ball, strike, out, or get a hit off of.

Vanderbilt Pitcher 1

For the first pitcher, I decided to look at the count and outs to determine what pitch would be thrown. Before getting to a higher level of baseball, it was common to see a pattern in pitch sequencing, where fastballs would mostly be thrown until a strikeout count where a curveball was then thrown. However, one you reached high school this was a lot less common and you could get any pitch at any time.

Looking at the graph, it can be seen that Balls and Strikes made up 80.29% of variability. Given that teams attempt to get one out at a time when it comes to pitch sequencing (that is a strikeout), I honestly view this as a decent predictor. I think it would be best should it be slightly more random, meaning count is less reliable to determine PitchType, but for pitchers to continue pitching for a long time, pitch sequencing cannot be completely random. My personal opinion is count should explain anywhere from 65-80/% of variability in pitch type. As the relative accuracy is 72.2/%, this is a decent model for pitch sequencing.

Vandy1 <- data.table::fread("/home/students/goardmm/SportsAnalyticsClass/Assignment4/vandy_1.csv")
set.seed(7)
pitch_cluster1 <- kmeans(Vandy1[,c(2, 3, 4)], 6, nstart = 20)

So this pitcher might throw a lot fastballs inside and curveballs outside. Looking at the relative accuracy, it appears using location is apporximately 68.3/% accurate.
